"{    \"translations\": [        {            \"english_version\": \"Vladimir Putin said that all the attackers responsible for storming a concert hall near Moscow had been arrested by Russian authorities. The terror attack, which took place on Friday night, is understood to have killed at least 140 people and wounded many others. The region\u2019s governor said the death toll could 'rise significantly'. American officials said that an affiliate of Islamic State could be behind the attack, after the group claimed responsibility. Mr Putin tried to connect the attackers to Ukraine: he claimed they were caught while fleeing to the border. Ukraine\u2019s government firmly denied having any involvement in the attack.\",            \"english_title\": \"Putin Announces Arrest of Attackers in Moscow Concert Hall Incident\",            \"translated_version\": \"Vladimir Putin announced that Russian authorities have arrested all the attackers who stormed a concert hall near Moscow. The attack happened on Friday night and resulted in the deaths of at least 140 people with many others injured. The governor of the region mentioned that the death toll might increase. There are suspicions that an affiliate of Islamic State could be responsible for the attack. Mr Putin suggested a link between the attackers and Ukraine, but Ukraine denied any involvement.\",            \"translated_title\": \"Putin Anuncia Arresto de Atacantes en Incidente de Sala de Conciertos en Mosc\u00fa\"        },        {            \"english_version\": \"China and Russia vetoed a draft resolution for an immediate ceasefire in Gaza at the UN Security Council. There were 11 votes in favour of the resolution, which was put forward by America; only Algeria, of the non-permanent members, joined China and Russia to vote against the text. The resolution tied a ceasefire deal to the release of Israeli hostages held by Hamas.\",            \"english_title\": \"China and Russia Veto Ceasefire Resolution in Gaza\",            \"translated_version\": \"China and Russia blocked a proposed resolution for an immediate ceasefire in Gaza at the UN Security Council. The resolution, supported by 11 votes, was introduced by America. Algeria was the only non-permanent member to join China and Russia in voting against the resolution. The resolution linked the ceasefire to the release of Israeli hostages held by Hamas.\",            \"translated_title\": \"China y Rusia Vetan Resoluci\u00f3n de Alto al Fuego en Gaza\"        },        {            \"english_version\": \"Slovakia\u2019s high-stakes election. Slovaks choose their new president on Saturday. Ivan Kor\u00e7ok, a pro-Western former diplomat, and Peter Pelligrini, a close ally of the populist prime minister, Robert Fico, are expected to progress to the second round on April 6th. Since his return to power in October, Mr Fico has attacked independent institutions. The liberal outgoing president, Zuzana Caputova, managed to hold off his attempts to soften anti-corruption laws. But Mr Pelligrini, a former member of Mr Fico\u2019s Smer party, would be more amenable.\",            \"english_title\": \"Slovakia's Presidential Election\",            \"translated_version\": \"Slovakia is having a crucial election where the new president will be chosen. Ivan Kor\u00e7ok, a pro-Western former diplomat, and Peter Pelligrini, a close ally of the populist prime minister, Robert Fico, are likely to advance to the second round on April 6th. Mr Fico has been criticized for targeting independent institutions since his return to power. The current president, Zuzana Caputova, successfully resisted his efforts to weaken anti-corruption laws. However, Mr Pelligrini, a former member of Mr Fico\u2019s party, may be more cooperative.\",            \"translated_title\": \"Elecci\u00f3n Presidencial en Eslovaquia\"        },        {            \"english_version\": \"Pakistan\u2019s gloomy Day. On Saturday the country celebrates Pakistan Day. It commemorates the Lahore Resolution of 1940, which called for a separate homeland for India\u2019s Muslims and laid the foundation for the country\u2019s creation. But this year there is little reason to cheer. The country faces all sorts of problems. Inflation is running high. Public finances are precarious as the government awaits $1.1bn in emergency funding from the IMF. Terrorism continues to plague the country. On Wednesday Baloch-separatist militants attacked the port of Gwadar, the centrepiece of the China-Pakistan Economic Corridor. Stability is badly needed.\",            \"english_title\": \"Pakistan Day Celebrations Amid Challenges\",            \"translated_version\": \"Pakistan is observing Pakistan Day on Saturday, which marks the Lahore Resolution of 1940 that led to the creation of the country. However, this year's celebrations are subdued due to various challenges. The nation is grappling with high inflation, fragile public finances awaiting emergency funding from the IMF, and ongoing terrorism issues. Recently, Baloch-separatist militants targeted the Gwadar port, a key part of the China-Pakistan Economic Corridor, highlighting the need for stability.\",            \"translated_title\": \"Celebraciones del D\u00eda de Pakist\u00e1n en Medio de Desaf\u00edos\"        },        {            \"english_version\": \"The green light at the end of the tunnel. On Saturday, between 8.30pm and 9.30pm local time around the world, lights will go out. That, at least, is the hope of the World Wildlife Fund, a charity which organises an annual 'Earth Hour'. The action is more symbolic than practical: using figures for 2021, a crude calculation suggests that knocking out all of the world\u2019s electricity for one hour would reduce consumption by about three terawatt-hours, cutting carbon emissions by at most 1.7 megatons (about 0.004% of the annual total). And emissions from global electricity use have grown steadily since the first Earth Hour in 2007, reaching their highest level in 2023.\",            \"english_title\": \"Earth Hour's Symbolic Impact on Energy Consumption\",            \"translated_version\": \"The World Wildlife Fund organizes an annual 'Earth Hour' where lights are turned off globally between 8.30pm and 9.30pm local time. This symbolic gesture aims to reduce electricity consumption and carbon emissions, although the impact is minimal. Despite the initiative, global electricity emissions have continued to rise since the inception of Earth Hour in 2007, reaching peak levels in 2023.\",            \"translated_title\": \"Impacto Simb\u00f3lico de la Hora del Planeta en el Consumo de Energ\u00eda\"        }    ]}"